        <div id="content">
     	  <p>
	The financial sector has long been a magnet for many of America&rsquo;s best students. A new program called HackNY is providing top students with an opportunity to work in a sector of more concrete economic value.</p>
<p>
	<br />
	The reasons for working in the financial sector are myriad. For one thing, it is a &ldquo;real&rdquo; job, right off the bat, with steady, if oppressive, hours. In addition, most financial firms have names that parents (or potential girlfriends) will recognize. Finally, the salary and benefits are usually of a level beyond comparison to entry-level jobs in almost any other sector of the economy. And, you get to live in New York City.</p>
<p>
	<br />
	The financial crisis of 2008, however, took at least some of the luster of financial sector jobs. While many graduates have no doubt found working on Wall Street or thereabouts more than justifiable, it is easy to see how others with talent in computer science, math, and related fields have chafed at the notion of working for a part of the economy that seems so rankly self-serving.</p>
<p>
	<br />
	Enter HackNY. Created just this past winter by professors at Columbia, <span class="caps">NYU</span>, and a technology start-up executive, the program pays and houses twelve students selected through a competitive process to intern with technology-related start-ups in New York City. The program was founded with the intent of establishing greater links between academia and the New York technology community, and perhaps diverging somewhat the river of students between America&rsquo;s top universities and Wall Street&rsquo;s top financial firms.</p>
<p>
	<br />
	Students participating in the program said <a href="http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052748703302604575294740285039332.html" target="_blank">their experiences have been eye opening and caused them to reconsider their career</a>, according to a report in the Wall Street Journal. Tech start-ups, likewise, have said that the program is making it more likely that they will be able to attract high-achieving graduates.</p>
<p>
	<br />
	It is nice to see such concerted efforts to discourage from making a knee-jerk decision to join the well-paying financial sector. Too often, it seems, top-students simply want to take the fast track to Wall Street or a top-tier law school. It is difficult to blame them, but America will be better served if its top academic talent is presented with options beyond the legal and financial sectors. After all, it is not only Goldman Sachs and Sullivan and Cromwell that need or deserve top talent. If the American economy is going to continue to thrive in the 21st century, technology and other companies need it as well.</p>


	      	    <p><em>Christopher Eldred is a staff writer for Campus Progress. He attends Claremont McKenna College.</em></p>
	
	</div>

</div>




											
				
						
		
		
 
		
 

